Remarks.
The head and tergites are strongly punctate; the forcipules broadened, significantly extended beyond the cephalic plate (
Fig. 23
), the trochanteroprefemur is slightly concave on the inner surface, with an almost straight, ventral, chitinous rib (
Fig. 24
). All males have T 14 and Tim broadened and serrate, especially strongly broadened is T 14, their surface roughly rugose (
Figs 22
& 
26
). In addition, some specimens show serrate edges of T 13 and slightly serrate posterolateral edges of T 12. In all males, 15F are thickened, with two distinct sulci, i.e. a poorly expressed dorsolateral sulcus and a deep dorsal sulcus, the latter forming apically a round tubercle supporting a cluster of thick and short setae; some specimens in addition with 1 or 2 poorly expressed dorsal sulci on 15P; 15Ti with a barely visible dorsolateral sulcus. In most males, very fine and dense setae cover rear halves of SS 14–15, as well as 14C, 13P, F and Ti ventrally. Tarsi 1–13 with two ventral tarsal pectens.
